# Repository Pattern

## Structure

Each domain entity has a repository interface in `org.springframework.samples.petclinic.repository` and three profile-activated implementations:

| Profile | Package | Style |
|---------|---------|-------|
| `spring-data-jpa` (default) | `repository/springdatajpa/` | Spring Data `Repository<T, ID>` interface + custom `*Override` for delete |
| `jpa` | `repository/jpa/` | `@PersistenceContext EntityManager` |
| `jdbc` | `repository/jdbc/` | `NamedParameterJdbcTemplate` + row mappers |

## Rules

- Controllers and services depend ONLY on the repository interface, never on an implementation
- Each implementation class MUST be annotated with its `@Profile` (e.g., `@Profile("spring-data-jpa")`)
- Spring Data JPA repos that need custom delete logic use an `*Override` interface + `*Impl` class
- JDBC implementations manage join tables manually (e.g., `vet_specialties`) in `save()` and `delete()`

## Adding a new repository

1. Define the interface in `repository/` with CRUD methods
2. Create implementations in all three profile packages
3. Inject it into `ClinicServiceImpl` (or `UserServiceImpl` for auth)
4. Annotate each implementation with the correct `@Profile`
